description: PURPOSE:   The purpose of our workshop is to educate and empower individuals by addressing the prominent issue of menstrual hygiene, which can significantly impact the mental and physical health of all individuals who menstruate. The event will feature a presentation on "Menstrual Hygiene, Safe Sex, and Women’s Rights: What to Know and How We’re Involved," aiming to raise awareness and promote dialogue on these crucial topics.                 HANDS-ON ACTIVITY: The workshop will involve hands-on activities, specifically the creation of menstrual bracelets, which serve as both a symbol and a conversation starter regarding menstrual health and rights. Additionally, we will continue the drive initiated during Douglass' International Women's Day Event, encouraging attendees to contribute to our menstrual hygiene drive. Participants who bring donations will receive double raffle tickets for a care package giveaway.               FOOD: Dunkin- Munchkins & Hot ChocolateGOAL: Raise donations, spread awareness and educate. Make a menstrual bracelet for yourself, for a peer or a friendly stranger:)   DOUGLASS EVENT CREDIT:    ****All Douglass women in a Knowledge and Power course will receive event credit for attending!!
location: Kathleen W. Ludwig Global Village Living Learning Center
name: Making Menstrual Bracelets: A GLOBAL SYMBOL Workshop

description: RUSynapse is a program where we pair pre-medical Rutgers students with medical student mentors at Robert Wood Johnson Medical School. The goal of this is to provide pre-medical students with an additional resource as they navigate their pre-medical years and the medical school application process. In addition to being paired with a mentor, several mentor-mentee pairs will be "bundled together" based on some answers to this form. This will give students access to individualized help from their own mentor, as well as expertise on a wide variety of topics from multiple medical students. As of now, this program is prioritizing sophomores and above, but freshman can still apply!   Please fill out the form below by Friday, March 8th at 11:59 pm in its entirety so that we can best match you to a mentor and bundle that meet your needs and goals. All information will be kept confidential and will only be shared with the medical student coordinators and your individual mentor.     https://forms.gle/ysuzhVk5Ki6g94aeA   We look forward to reading your responses!   If you have any questions, please email Namarata Battula (nb638@rwjms.rutgers.edu), Hunter Skroczky (hs1154@rwjms.rutgers.edu), or Parth Modi (pm783@rwjms.rutgers.edu).
name: RUSynapse Event

description: Picture this: it's late April, you've survived the job search process, and now you have at least two job offers to consider before you graduate- congratulations! Then it hits you: how do you figure out which offer is the best offer? Once you accept a position, what should you reasonably expect from your first day, week, and month(s) on the job? You had a four-year plan for high school and college, but should you make a similar plan now that you're about to be a young professional in the workplace? You've officially entered into your Adulting 101 period of life, and luckily for you the four Cultural Centers on campus and CES have collaborated to provide you with a panel discussion to answer these and many other Adulting 101 questions.   During this event you will: -hear from HR and employment experts on topics like offer negotiations and HR -speak with industry aficionados about must-know resources to leverage to have the best experience possible during your first few months on the job -strategize moves to make early in your career to set yourself up for successful goal-setting and advancement   This event is part of the #Rutgersworks Free Tuition Challenge. By attending this event, you will earn one stamp toward your Spring 2024 gameboard. Visit careers.rutgers.edu/challenge for more information.   For accommodation needs or requests, please email careers@echo.rutgers.edu.
name: Adulting 101: A C4 + CES Collaboration
organizationNames: Cultural Center Collaborative (Department at Rutgers University)

description: Abstract: "In this talk, I (as a grad student with an astrophysics background) will review some of the key figures and plans outlined in the Intergovernmental Panel on Climate Change Sixth Assessment Report. Although climate change is a global problem that is rooted in the structure of our economy and industries, this assessment hopefully gives us a way forward to focus on reducing the harm. This seminar will also have an interactive portion (so bring your laptops!). We will use the MIT EN-ROADS simulator and act as certain sectors while trying to reduce global emissions below +2 degrees C by 2100."
name: SSPAR - Climate Change: Reviewing IPCC AR6 results - Dilys Ruan

description: Join us on Thursday, March 7th, 2024, for an enlightening and harmonious evening as we present Speaker Edition: Modern Science Meets Vedic Philosophy, featuring the esteemed guest speaker Siddha Haridas. Embark on a captivating journey that bridges the gap between ancient wisdom and contemporary scientific revelations, offering a unique exploration into the convergence of Modern Science and Vedic Philosophy. Siddha Haridas, a distinguished speaker and scholar, will delve into the mysteries of the universe, discussing compelling topics such as the Big Bang, the lifecycle of the sun, and mass extinctions. Discover how the timeless wisdom of the Vedic sages remarkably aligns with our current understanding of the cosmos, unveiling a tapestry of interconnected knowledge that transcends time and culture. As the evening unfolds, immerse yourself in the serenity of Kirtan meditation, a musical and spiritual practice that elevates the soul. Allow the soothing melodies to guide you towards inner peace and tranquility, creating a harmonious atmosphere that resonates with the themes of unity and interconnectedness. To conclude this enriching experience, indulge in a communal feast of free food, fostering a sense of community and shared celebration. Connect with like-minded individuals, engage in meaningful conversations, and savor a delightful array of culinary delights as we unite to nourish mind and body. Don't miss this opportunity to witness the convergence of ancient wisdom and modern science, harmonized through Siddha Haridas's lens, and partake in a truly immersive experience of Kirtan meditation and community gathering. Mark your calendars for Thursday, March 7th, 2024, and join us for an evening that promises to inspire, enlighten, and nourish the soul.
name: Speaker Edition: Modern Science Meets Vedic Philosophy

description: Thank you so much for your interest in the 2024 Rutgers New Brunswick UPitchNJ Competition!  Applications are now open!  Submit your application by February 15th!   What is UPitchNJ?   UPitchNJ is an annual statewide collegiate startup competition in partnership with Nokia Bell Labs. Participating university sends one undergraduate student team that had developed a startup idea, or had launched a startup, to compete for cash prizes. The selected student team will have the opportunity to receive mentoring from Nokia Bell Labs executives and research scientists leading up to the competition.   UPitchNJ’s aim is to highlight the ingenuity and creativity of today’s college entrepreneurs, whom are increasingly launching businesses from their dorm rooms.  As entrepreneurship educators in New Jersey, they want to provide entrepreneurial students with a networking forum with other students, mentors and potential investors. For the 2024 UPitchNJ competition, Rutgers University New Brunswick will send ONE team to compete with other participating universities/colleges. To determine which team will represent Rutgers, your team must complete this application and attend the Rutgers UPitchNJ Competition on Friday, February 24, 2024 (exact event time is to be determined). The Rutgers UPitchNJ Competition will be a preliminary round, where your team will present your idea and elevator pitch to a group of judges. Depending on the number of teams that participate in the preliminary round, we will determine if it is necessary to move finalist to a secondary round or if we will proceed with one team.   Requirements- Teams can consist of up to 5 members, all members being Rutgers University New Brunswick students - Have a startup/idea for innovation - Submit this application before the deadline (listed below) - Attend Rutgers UPitchNJ Competition on Friday, February 24, 2024. Expect to come prepared to present your idea and elevator pitch (more specific details will be sent closer to the date)      Key Dates Application Closes: Thursday, February 15, 2024Notification Date: Wednesday, February 28, 2024 Rutgers UPitchNJ Competition: Friday, March 8, 2024   If you have any questions, please email innovate@njaes.rutgers.edu
location: The Hatchery Innovation Studio, Lower Level Alexander Library
name: UPitchNJ Rutgers Competition - Apply by February 15, 2024!

description: Celebrate the end of the academic year by joining Douglass staff, the Voorhees Choir, and fellow students for the annual Sacred Path Ceremony. One of Douglass' oldest traditions, the Sacred Path ceremony recognizes student achievement and fosters Douglass's unique community. Join your fellow Douglass classmates, alumnae, friends, and family as each class is honored with a symbol representing the different class years. After you receive your charm, head to the ceremonial fires on the sacred path to make a wish!  Students should show their pride by wearing their class year colors (first years wear white, sophomores wear pink, juniors wear red, and seniors wear black). Every student will receive a charm, a token representing her class. All Douglass students, family, faculty, and alumnae are welcome! Refreshments will be provided at Ludwig immediately following the ceremony.  *Students in Knowledge & Power will receive 2 points towards their Douglass event requirements*
name: Sacred Path 2024

Attendance for our Dress Rehearsal and Concert are mandatory so please note on the form which dates you are not available. description: Attention all Douglass STEM students! Are you interested in learning about potential career opportunities, different career paths, and networking with professionals in your field of study?
